DETAILS
1. Signature and usage
- Number.isInteger(value) takes one argument value and returns boolean.
- Typical use: validate API inputs where integer is required before loops or allocation.

2. Return value rules
- true if value is of type number and floor(value) === value (within FP precision); false otherwise.
- Explicit false for NaN and Infinity.

3. Floating point precision caveats
- Because JS numbers are IEEE-754 doubles, fractional values may round to integers for representation; tests near MAX_SAFE_INTEGER may be unreliable.
- Example: Number.isInteger(5.0000000000000001) -> true because underlying representation equals 5.

4. Implementation guidance and alternatives
- For exact integer checks on large integers, accept BigInt and use typeof value === 'bigint'.
- Use Number.isSafeInteger(value) when requiring safe integer range within Number.MIN_SAFE_INTEGER..Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER.

REFERENCE DETAILS
- Signature: Number.isInteger(value): boolean
- Related: Number.isSafeInteger(value) -> boolean — returns true when Number.isInteger(value) && Math.abs(value) <= Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER

SUPPLEMENTARY DETAILS
- Input validation example for runFizzBuzz API:
  - if (!Number.isInteger(end)) throw new TypeError('end must be integer')
  - if (end > Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER) consider rejecting or require BigInt input

